{"title_page": "Lois Leveen", "text_new": "{{cleanup|date=February 2011}}\n'''Lois M. Leveen''' is an American writer and educator based in Portland, Oregon.\n\n== Writing ==\n\n=== ''The Secrets of Mary Bowser'', Civil War fiction and Historical nonfiction ===\nLeveen's first novel was '''''The Secrets of Mary Bowser''''' (2012, William Morrow, {{ISBN|9780062107916}}), based on the life of [[Mary Bowser]], \"a Richmond slave who became a spy for the Union army.\"<ref>Harper Collins Author page, retrieved 20 July 2012 http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/38440/Lois_Leveen/index.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628223930/http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/38440/Lois_Leveen/index.aspx |date=2012-06-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=The North of the South | work=The New York Times Disunion blog  | url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/24/the-north-of-the-south/ | date=24 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=The Other Major Anderson | work=The New York Times Disunion blog  | url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/18/the-other-major-anderson/ | date=18 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Mary Bowser novel | work=Mary Bowser novel | url=http://loisleveen.com/marybowser.html | accessdate=24 January 2011}}</ref> In August 2012, the novel was chosen as a Target club pick<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.target.com/p/the-secrets-of-mary-bowser-by-lois-leveen-target-club-pick-paperback/-/A-14039660|title=Target Club Pick Aug 2012: The Secrets of Mary B... : Target|work=Target}}</ref> and named one of the Oregonian's \"Top 10 Northwest Books of 2012.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2012/12/the_oregonians_top_10_northwes_10.html|title=The Oregonian's top 10 Northwest books of 2012: No. 10 'The Secrets of Mary Bowser' by Lois Leveen|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLeveen also writes historical articles about the Civil War as a contributor to the ''New York Times'' Disunion blog, which tracks the causes of the Civil War.  She has written about the life of Mary Bowser in \"[http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/21/a-black-spy-in-the-confederate-white-house/ A Black Spy in the Confederate White House],\" as well as articles on [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/24/the-north-of-the-south/ the enslaved and free black community in Richmond, Virginia]; on [[Joseph Reid Anderson]], controversial [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/18/the-other-major-anderson/ owner of Tredegar Ironworks]; and on [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/22/richmonds-medical-miracle/ Chimborazo, a large army hospital] in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]].\n\nLeveen's most recent research, \"[https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-vanishing-black-woman-spy-reappears/# The Vanishing Black Woman Spy Reappears],\" and \"[https://time.com/5609045/misremembering-mary-bowser/ What the 'Mary Bowser' Story Gets Wrong],\" focuses on the real woman on whom her novel is based, who is more accurately identified as Mary Richards Denman. Leveen in currently writing a nonfiction book about Mary Richards Denman.<ref>Lois Leveen, \"What the 'Mary Bowser' Story Gets Wrong.\" TIME https://time.com/5609045/misremembering-mary-bowser/ Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref><ref>Lois Leveen, \"The Vanishing Black Woman Spy Reappears.\" ''The Los Angeles Review of Books''. https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-vanishing-black-woman-spy-reappears/# Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref>\n\n=== ''Juliet's Nurse'' ===\nLeveen's second novel ''''' Juliet's Nurse''''' (2014, Simon & Schuster, {{ISBN|9781476757445}}) reimagines the story of Shakespeare's [[Romeo and Juliet]] from the point of view of [[Nurse (Romeo and Juliet)|the nurse]].<ref>Simon and Schuster author page, retrieved 19 April 2014 http://books.simonandschuster.com/Juliets-Nurse/Lois-Leveen/9781476757445</ref> Prior to the book's publication, Leveen gave talks at conferences around the world about how her studies of fourteenth-century Italian history shaped the novel.<ref>Framing Premodern Desires Conference page retrieved 19 April 2014 http://www.utu.fi/en/units/hum/sites/tucemems/news-and-events/colloquiums/premoderndesires/Pages/Program.aspx</ref><ref>Shakespeare 450 Conference page retrieved 19 April 2014 http://www.shakespeareanniversary.org/shake450/panels/panel-16-shakespeare-and-architecture/</ref> As part of her research for this project, Leveen developed an interest in apiculture and worked with the City of Portland to ease regulations for local beekeepers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandurbanbeekeepers.org/2015/03/29/march-2015-beeline/|title=March 2015 Beeline \u2013 Portland Urban Beekeepers|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Creative Nonfiction ===\n\nHer essay \"The Ice Age\", about her father's mid-life crisis as a figure skater appeared in ''The Oregon Literary Review'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Ice Age | work=Oregon Literary Review, Vol. 3, No. 1 | url=http://orelitrev.startlogic.com/v3n1/OLR-leveen.htm | date=Winter\u2013Spring 2008 | access-date=2010-11-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716132226/http://orelitrev.startlogic.com/v3n1/OLR-leveen.htm# | archive-date=2011-07-16 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHer Christmas-themed piece \"Gay Apparel\" was featured in the 2010 Lambda Literary Award-winning<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambdaliterary.org/winners-finalists/05/10/2010-awards-finalists-winners/|title=Lambda Literary|work=Lambda Literary}}</ref> anthology ''Portland Queer''<ref>Gore, Ariel (ed.).  Portland Queer: Tales of the Rose City. Lit Star Press, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Portland-centric anthology on gay life | url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2009/06/portlandcentric_anthology_on_g.html | work=The Oregonian | date=June 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, her short story describing her experiences with and love for the sidewalk \"Free Box\"  was published in an anthology called, [http://ourportlandstory.com/stories?id=715 Our Portland Story],<ref>Our Portland Story, Volume One.</ref> a book about Portland, Oregon by Portlanders.\n\n=== Critical Essays ===\n\nIn 2008 her piece critical of the television character [[Dora the Explorer]]  appeared in ''Bitch Magazine''<ref>{{cite web | author=Leveen, Lois | title=Factory Girl: Dora the Explorer and the Dirty Secrets of the Global Industrial Economy | work=Bitch Magazine Issue 40, \"Genesis\", Summer 2008. | url=http://bitchmagazine.org/article/factory-girl}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, her essay \"Pitiful strategies : Richard Delgado's legal storytelling and the politics of racial representation\" appeared in [http://www.worldcat.org/title/crossroutes-the-meanings-of-race-for-the-21st-century/oclc/52361257 CrossRoutes, the meanings of \"race\" for the 21st century], an international collection of critical race theory.<ref>Boi, Paola (ed.), ''CrossRoutes, the meanings of \"race\" for the 21st century''.  M\u00fcnster : Lit ; Piscataway, NJ : Distributed in North America by Transaction Publishers, 2003.</ref>\n\n=== Poetry ===\n\nHer poem \"Welcome water\" is inscribed on the wall of a hospital in Oregon.<ref>Poetry for westside medical center, retrieved April 19, 2014 {{cite web |url=https://northwest-hospitals.kaiserpermanente.org/about-our-hospitals/medianews/poetry-westside-medical-center |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140419201339/https://northwest-hospitals.kaiserpermanente.org/about-our-hospitals/medianews/poetry-westside-medical-center |archivedate=2014-04-19 }}</ref>\n\nHer poem \"Cognative Dissonance\" was featured in the Jewish feminist journal ''Bridges'' in 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/bridges_a_jewish_feminists_journal/v014/14.2.leveen.pdf|title=Bridges|work=jhu.edu}}</ref>\n\nHer poem \"Walloon at Walgreens\" appeared in [http://monkeypuzzlepress.com/magazines/issue-8/ Monkey Puzzle # 8] in 2009<ref>\"Walloon at Walgreens,\" in ''Monkey Puzzle #8''.  Denver, Colorado: Monkey Puzzle Press, 2009</ref>\n\n=== Columns ===\n\nLeveen is Jewish.  She published several articles for the Daily Forward in June 2012.[[File:<ref>The Daily Forward, 28 June 2012, http://blogs.forward.com/the-arty-semite/tags/lois-leveen/{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved 7/20/2012</ref>]]  Since 2008 she has been an ethics columnist (\"The Shmeticist\") for The Jew and the Carrot, a Jewish food blog.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jcarrot.org/author/lois | title=The Jew and the Carrot}}</ref>  She has also written for Interfaith Family<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/relationships/marriage_and_relationships/Interfaith_Marriage_Sometimes_Its_Easier.shtml?rd=2 | title=Interfaith Family}}</ref> and she has spoken at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QIgah9SUIw8&feature=relmfu Oregon Jewish Museum].\n\n== Medical Humanities ==\n\nLeveen is active in the field of [[medical humanities]]. In 2016-2017, she was a Kienle Scholar in Medical Humanities at Penn State College of Medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.psu.edu/kienlecenter/colloquium/|title=2016 Colloquium|website=sites.psu.edu|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> \n\nHer publications in this field include \"[https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-hidden-dying-of-doctors-what-the-humanities-can-teach-medicine-and-why-we-all-need-medicine-to-learn-it/#! The Hidden Dying of Doctors: What the Humanities Can Teach Medicine and Why We All Need Medicine to Learn it],\"<ref>Lois Leveen, \"The Hidden Dying of Doctors,\" ''The Los Angeles Review of Books''.  https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-hidden-dying-of-doctors-what-the-humanities-can-teach-medicine-and-why-we-all-need-medicine-to-learn-it/#! Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref> and \"[http://www.thepermanentejournal.org/issues/43-the-permanente-journal/original-research-and-contributions/6532-finding-purpose-honing-the-practice-of-making-meaning-in-medicine.html Finding Purpose: Honing the Practice of Making Meaning in Medicine],\" which appeared in a medical journal.<ref>Lois Leveen, \"Finding Purpose: Honing the Practice of Making Meaning in Medicine.\" ''Permanente Journal'' 2017. https://doi.org/10.7812/TPP/17-048 Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Teaching ==\n\nThe non-profit organization Literary Arts has run  [http://www.literary-arts.org/delve/ \"Delve Readers' Seminars\"] since 2005.  Lois Leveen has led several of these:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.literary-arts.org/index.php?article=956 | title=Past Delve Seminars}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://literary-arts.org/delve-program-guide-lois-leveen/|title=Delve Program Guide: Lois Leveen|website=Literary Arts|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\n2019:\n:Talking to Grief -- Literary Explorations of Loss\n2018:\n:Works of Heart -- Literature and Medical Humanities\n2016 and 2017:\n:Cease Not Until Death\n2012:\n:Reading the Literary Lineage of The Girl Who Fell from the Sky\n2011:\n:Breaking the Yoke: The Anti-Slavery Literature that Changed America\n:Call and Response: Delving into African American Art & Literature\n2010: \n:We, Too, Sing America: 20th-Century Writers & The Legacy Of Whitman\n:Illustrating Identity In The Age Of The Graphic Novel\n:Exploding The Canon: How Native American, Asian American And Latina Women Remade American Literature\n2009:\n:Shakespeare: The Tragedies of Empire\n2008:\n:Shakespeare: The Tragedies of Empire\n:Charles Dickens: Bleak House\n:William Faulkner & Toni Morrison: Absalom, Absalom! & Beloved\n:Nathaniel Hawthorne & Gustave Flaubert: The Scarlet Letter & Madame Bovary\n2007:\n:Ralph Ellison: Invisible Man\n2006:\n:Harriet Beecher Stowe: Uncle Tom\u2019s Cabin\n\nShe previously taught at Reed College<ref>{{cite web|title=Reed Magazine|url=http://www.reed.edu/reed_magazine/feb2003/features/what_tech_teaches/6.html}}</ref>  and UCLA<ref>{{cite web|title=UCLA course website|url=http://www.college.ucla.edu/ge_archive/clusters_archive/1998-1999/20abc.htm|access-date=2012-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723052339/http://www.college.ucla.edu/ge_archive/clusters_archive/1998-1999/20abc.htm#|archive-date=2010-07-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Radio ==\n\nLois Leveen read her personal essay on pseudo-death and rising long-distance rates on episode 68 of the NPR variety show Live Wire in June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livewireradio.org/node/114|title=Episode 68|work=livewireradio.org}}</ref>\n\n== Television: Mission Hill ==\n\nLois was the inspiration and model for the character of Natalie Leibowitz-Hernandez on the [[Adult Swim]] cartoon [[Mission Hill (TV series)|Mission Hill]],<ref>https://twitter.com/thatbilloakley/status/2150587298750464{{dead link|date=December 2017|fix-attempted=yes|bot=TweetCiteBot}}</ref> which was created by three of her long-time friends.  She auditioned for the voice of her own character, but actress [[Vicki Lewis]] was determined to be even more \"Lois-y\" than Lois Leveen herself, and she was cast in the role instead.<ref>https://twitter.com/thatbilloakley/status/2150853913870336{{dead link|date=December 2017|fix-attempted=yes|bot=TweetCiteBot}}</ref>\n\n== Multimedia ==\n\nSince 2007 Leveen and her partner have created five videos, including [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xHlrOiuO6zE Four Act Foreman] with characters drawn from their idiosyncratic selection of objects as part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20110317044140/http://www.performanceworksnw.org/ Performance Works NorthWest's] annual Richard Foreman Mini-Festival.  Lois served on the Board of Portland's Performance Works NorthWest from 2006 to 2010.\n\nShe also served as academic advisor for two multimedia series [http://www.learner.org/courses/amerhistory/ America's History in the Making] and [http://www.learner.org/workshops/artifacts/ Artifacts and Fiction], produced by Annenberg/CPB.\n\n== Music ==\nAfter an encounter with Bay Area accordion and pyrotechnic maestro Kimrick Smythe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smythesaccordioncenter.com/|title=Smythe's Accordion Center|work=smythesaccordioncenter.com}}</ref> Lois embraced the accordion fully. Her increasing proficiency and resurrection of Christmas carols and Yiddish<ref>[[Yiddish language]]</ref> standards became a staple of the annual San Francisco Lingerie Thanksgiving.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Mix | work=San Francisco Bay Guardian | date=December 3, 2003 | url=http://www.sfbg.com/38/10/x_the_mix.html}}</ref> She plays accordion in The Stumptown Family Ramblers, a band created by [[Sarah Dougher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheStumptownFamilyRamblers?filter=1|title=The Stumptown Family Ramblers|work=Facebook}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahdougher.net/biography/|title=Biography|work=sarahdougher.net}}</ref>\n\nShe graduated from [[Harvard College]], [[University of Southern California]], and [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref>http://loisleveen.com/index.php/loisleveen/bio</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.loisleveen.com|Author's official website}}\n* [http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/mary-bowser-freed-slave-civil-war-spy/ Leveen discusses ''The Secrets of Mary Bowser''] at the [[Pritzker Military Museum & Library]] on January 18, 2013\n* {{C-SPAN|Lois Leveen}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leveen, Lois M.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Educators from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Writers from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|date=February 2011}}\n'''Lois M. Leveen''' is an American writer and educator based in Portland, Oregon.\n\n== Writing ==\n\n=== ''The Secrets of Mary Bowser'', Civil War fiction and Historical nonfiction ===\nLeveen's first novel was '''''The Secrets of Mary Bowser''''' (2012, William Morrow, {{ISBN|9780062107916}}), based on the life of [[Mary Bowser]], \"a Richmond slave who became a spy for the Union army.\"<ref>Harper Collins Author page, retrieved 20 July 2012 http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/38440/Lois_Leveen/index.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628223930/http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/38440/Lois_Leveen/index.aspx |date=2012-06-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=The North of the South | work=The New York Times Disunion blog  | url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/24/the-north-of-the-south/ | date=24 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=The Other Major Anderson | work=The New York Times Disunion blog  | url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/18/the-other-major-anderson/ | date=18 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Mary Bowser novel | work=Mary Bowser novel | url=http://loisleveen.com/marybowser.html | accessdate=24 January 2011}}</ref> In August 2012, the novel was chosen as a Target club pick<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.target.com/p/the-secrets-of-mary-bowser-by-lois-leveen-target-club-pick-paperback/-/A-14039660|title=Target Club Pick Aug 2012: The Secrets of Mary B... : Target|work=Target}}</ref> and named one of the Oregonian's \"Top 10 Northwest Books of 2012.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2012/12/the_oregonians_top_10_northwes_10.html|title=The Oregonian's top 10 Northwest books of 2012: No. 10 'The Secrets of Mary Bowser' by Lois Leveen|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLeveen also writes historical articles about the Civil War as a contributor to the ''New York Times'' Disunion blog, which tracks the causes of the Civil War.  She has written about the life of Mary Bowser in \"[http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/21/a-black-spy-in-the-confederate-white-house/ A Black Spy in the Confederate White House],\" as well as articles on [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/24/the-north-of-the-south/ the enslaved and free black community in Richmond, Virginia]; on [[Joseph Reid Anderson]], controversial [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/18/the-other-major-anderson/ owner of Tredegar Ironworks]; and on [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/22/richmonds-medical-miracle/ Chimborazo, a large army hospital] in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]].\n\nLeveen's most recent research, \"[https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-vanishing-black-woman-spy-reappears/# The Vanishing Black Woman Spy Reappears],\" and \"[https://time.com/5609045/misremembering-mary-bowser/ What the 'Mary Bowser' Story Gets Wrong],\" focuses on the real woman on whom her novel is based, who is more accurately identified as Mary Richards Denman. Leveen in currently writing a nonfiction book about Mary Richards Denman.<ref>Lois Leveen, \"What the 'Mary Bowser' Story Gets Wrong.\" TIME https://time.com/5609045/misremembering-mary-bowser/ Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref><ref>Lois Leveen, \"The Vanishing Black Woman Spy Reappears.\" ''The Los Angeles Review of Books''. https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-vanishing-black-woman-spy-reappears/# Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref>\n\n=== ''Juliet's Nurse'' ===\nLeveen's second novel ''''' Juliet's Nurse''''' (2014, Simon & Schuster, {{ISBN|9781476757445}}) reimagines the story of Shakespeare's [[Romeo and Juliet]] from the point of view of [[Nurse (Romeo and Juliet)|the nurse]].<ref>Simon and Schuster author page, retrieved 19 April 2014 http://books.simonandschuster.com/Juliets-Nurse/Lois-Leveen/9781476757445</ref> Prior to the book's publication, Leveen gave talks at conferences around the world about how her studies of fourteenth-century Italian history shaped the novel.<ref>Framing Premodern Desires Conference page retrieved 19 April 2014 http://www.utu.fi/en/units/hum/sites/tucemems/news-and-events/colloquiums/premoderndesires/Pages/Program.aspx</ref><ref>Shakespeare 450 Conference page retrieved 19 April 2014 http://www.shakespeareanniversary.org/shake450/panels/panel-16-shakespeare-and-architecture/</ref> As part of her research for this project, Leveen developed an interest in apiculture and worked with the City of Portland to ease regulations for local beekeepers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portlandurbanbeekeepers.org/2015/03/29/march-2015-beeline/|title=March 2015 Beeline \u2013 Portland Urban Beekeepers|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Creative Nonfiction ===\n\nHer essay \"The Ice Age\", about her father's mid-life crisis as a figure skater appeared in ''The Oregon Literary Review'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Ice Age | work=Oregon Literary Review, Vol. 3, No. 1 | url=http://orelitrev.startlogic.com/v3n1/OLR-leveen.htm | date=Winter\u2013Spring 2008 | access-date=2010-11-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716132226/http://orelitrev.startlogic.com/v3n1/OLR-leveen.htm# | archive-date=2011-07-16 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHer Christmas-themed piece \"Gay Apparel\" was featured in the 2010 Lambda Literary Award winning<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lambdaliterary.org/winners-finalists/05/10/2010-awards-finalists-winners/|title=Lambda Literary|work=Lambda Literary}}</ref> anthology ''Portland Queer''<ref>Gore, Ariel (ed.).  Portland Queer: Tales of the Rose City. Lit Star Press, 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Portland-centric anthology on gay life | url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2009/06/portlandcentric_anthology_on_g.html | work=The Oregonian | date=June 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, her short story describing her experiences with and love for the sidewalk \"Free Box\"  was published in an anthology called, [http://ourportlandstory.com/stories?id=715 Our Portland Story],<ref>Our Portland Story, Volume One.</ref> a book about Portland, Oregon by Portlanders.\n\n=== Critical Essays ===\n\nIn 2008 her piece critical of the television character [[Dora the Explorer]]  appeared in ''Bitch Magazine''<ref>{{cite web | author=Leveen, Lois | title=Factory Girl: Dora the Explorer and the Dirty Secrets of the Global Industrial Economy | work=Bitch Magazine Issue 40, \"Genesis\", Summer 2008. | url=http://bitchmagazine.org/article/factory-girl}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, her essay \"Pitiful strategies : Richard Delgado's legal storytelling and the politics of racial representation\" appeared in [http://www.worldcat.org/title/crossroutes-the-meanings-of-race-for-the-21st-century/oclc/52361257 CrossRoutes, the meanings of \"race\" for the 21st century], an international collection of critical race theory.<ref>Boi, Paola (ed.), ''CrossRoutes, the meanings of \"race\" for the 21st century''.  M\u00fcnster : Lit ; Piscataway, NJ : Distributed in North America by Transaction Publishers, 2003.</ref>\n\n=== Poetry ===\n\nHer poem \"Welcome water\" is inscribed on the wall of a hospital in Oregon.<ref>Poetry for westside medical center, retrieved April 19, 2014 {{cite web |url=https://northwest-hospitals.kaiserpermanente.org/about-our-hospitals/medianews/poetry-westside-medical-center |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140419201339/https://northwest-hospitals.kaiserpermanente.org/about-our-hospitals/medianews/poetry-westside-medical-center |archivedate=2014-04-19 }}</ref>\n\nHer poem \"Cognative Dissonance\" was featured in the Jewish feminist journal ''Bridges'' in 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/bridges_a_jewish_feminists_journal/v014/14.2.leveen.pdf|title=Bridges|work=jhu.edu}}</ref>\n\nHer poem \"Walloon at Walgreens\" appeared in [http://monkeypuzzlepress.com/magazines/issue-8/ Monkey Puzzle # 8] in 2009<ref>\"Walloon at Walgreens,\" in ''Monkey Puzzle #8''.  Denver, Colorado: Monkey Puzzle Press, 2009</ref>\n\n=== Columns ===\n\nLeveen is Jewish.  She published several articles for the Daily Forward in June 2012.[[File:<ref>The Daily Forward, 28 June 2012, http://blogs.forward.com/the-arty-semite/tags/lois-leveen/{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved 7/20/2012</ref>]]  Since 2008 she has been an ethics columnist (\"The Shmeticist\") for The Jew and the Carrot, a Jewish food blog.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jcarrot.org/author/lois | title=The Jew and the Carrot}}</ref>  She has also written for Interfaith Family<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/relationships/marriage_and_relationships/Interfaith_Marriage_Sometimes_Its_Easier.shtml?rd=2 | title=Interfaith Family}}</ref> and she has spoken at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QIgah9SUIw8&feature=relmfu Oregon Jewish Museum].\n\n== Medical Humanities ==\n\nLeveen is active in the field of [[medical humanities]]. In 2016-2017, she was a Kienle Scholar in Medical Humanities at Penn State College of Medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.psu.edu/kienlecenter/colloquium/|title=2016 Colloquium|website=sites.psu.edu|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref> \n\nHer publications in this field include \"[https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-hidden-dying-of-doctors-what-the-humanities-can-teach-medicine-and-why-we-all-need-medicine-to-learn-it/#! The Hidden Dying of Doctors: What the Humanities Can Teach Medicine and Why We All Need Medicine to Learn it],\"<ref>Lois Leveen, \"The Hidden Dying of Doctors,\" ''The Los Angeles Review of Books''.  https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-hidden-dying-of-doctors-what-the-humanities-can-teach-medicine-and-why-we-all-need-medicine-to-learn-it/#! Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref> and \"[http://www.thepermanentejournal.org/issues/43-the-permanente-journal/original-research-and-contributions/6532-finding-purpose-honing-the-practice-of-making-meaning-in-medicine.html Finding Purpose: Honing the Practice of Making Meaning in Medicine],\" which appeared in a medical journal.<ref>Lois Leveen, \"Finding Purpose: Honing the Practice of Making Meaning in Medicine.\" ''Permanente Journal'' 2017. https://doi.org/10.7812/TPP/17-048 Retrieved July 20, 2019.</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Teaching ==\n\nThe non-profit organization Literary Arts has run  [http://www.literary-arts.org/delve/ \"Delve Readers' Seminars\"] since 2005.  Lois Leveen has led several of these:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.literary-arts.org/index.php?article=956 | title=Past Delve Seminars}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://literary-arts.org/delve-program-guide-lois-leveen/|title=Delve Program Guide: Lois Leveen|website=Literary Arts|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\n2019:\n:Talking to Grief -- Literary Explorations of Loss\n2018:\n:Works of Heart -- Literature and Medical Humanities\n2016 and 2017:\n:Cease Not Until Death\n2012:\n:Reading the Literary Lineage of The Girl Who Fell from the Sky\n2011:\n:Breaking the Yoke: The Anti-Slavery Literature that Changed America\n:Call and Response: Delving into African American Art & Literature\n2010: \n:We, Too, Sing America: 20th-Century Writers & The Legacy Of Whitman\n:Illustrating Identity In The Age Of The Graphic Novel\n:Exploding The Canon: How Native American, Asian American And Latina Women Remade American Literature\n2009:\n:Shakespeare: The Tragedies of Empire\n2008:\n:Shakespeare: The Tragedies of Empire\n:Charles Dickens: Bleak House\n:William Faulkner & Toni Morrison: Absalom, Absalom! & Beloved\n:Nathaniel Hawthorne & Gustave Flaubert: The Scarlet Letter & Madame Bovary\n2007:\n:Ralph Ellison: Invisible Man\n2006:\n:Harriet Beecher Stowe: Uncle Tom\u2019s Cabin\n\nShe previously taught at Reed College<ref>{{cite web|title=Reed Magazine|url=http://www.reed.edu/reed_magazine/feb2003/features/what_tech_teaches/6.html}}</ref>  and UCLA<ref>{{cite web|title=UCLA course website|url=http://www.college.ucla.edu/ge_archive/clusters_archive/1998-1999/20abc.htm|access-date=2012-04-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723052339/http://www.college.ucla.edu/ge_archive/clusters_archive/1998-1999/20abc.htm#|archive-date=2010-07-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Radio ==\n\nLois Leveen read her personal essay on pseudo-death and rising long-distance rates on episode 68 of the NPR variety show Live Wire in June 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livewireradio.org/node/114|title=Episode 68|work=livewireradio.org}}</ref>\n\n== Television: Mission Hill ==\n\nLois was the inspiration and model for the character of Natalie Leibowitz-Hernandez on the [[Adult Swim]] cartoon [[Mission Hill (TV series)|Mission Hill]],<ref>https://twitter.com/thatbilloakley/status/2150587298750464{{dead link|date=December 2017|fix-attempted=yes|bot=TweetCiteBot}}</ref> which was created by three of her long-time friends.  She auditioned for the voice of her own character, but actress [[Vicki Lewis]] was determined to be even more \"Lois-y\" than Lois Leveen herself, and she was cast in the role instead.<ref>https://twitter.com/thatbilloakley/status/2150853913870336{{dead link|date=December 2017|fix-attempted=yes|bot=TweetCiteBot}}</ref>\n\n== Multimedia ==\n\nSince 2007 Leveen and her partner have created five videos, including [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xHlrOiuO6zE Four Act Foreman] with characters drawn from their idiosyncratic selection of objects as part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20110317044140/http://www.performanceworksnw.org/ Performance Works NorthWest's] annual Richard Foreman Mini-Festival.  Lois served on the Board of Portland's Performance Works NorthWest from 2006 to 2010.\n\nShe also served as academic advisor for two multimedia series [http://www.learner.org/courses/amerhistory/ America's History in the Making] and [http://www.learner.org/workshops/artifacts/ Artifacts and Fiction], produced by Annenberg/CPB.\n\n== Music ==\nAfter an encounter with Bay Area accordion and pyrotechnic maestro Kimrick Smythe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smythesaccordioncenter.com/|title=Smythe's Accordion Center|work=smythesaccordioncenter.com}}</ref> Lois embraced the accordion fully. Her increasing proficiency and resurrection of Christmas carols and Yiddish<ref>[[Yiddish language]]</ref> standards became a staple of the annual San Francisco Lingerie Thanksgiving.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Mix | work=San Francisco Bay Guardian | date=December 3, 2003 | url=http://www.sfbg.com/38/10/x_the_mix.html}}</ref> She plays accordion in The Stumptown Family Ramblers, a band created by [[Sarah Dougher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheStumptownFamilyRamblers?filter=1|title=The Stumptown Family Ramblers|work=Facebook}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahdougher.net/biography/|title=Biography|work=sarahdougher.net}}</ref>\n\nShe graduated from [[Harvard College]], [[University of Southern California]], and [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref>http://loisleveen.com/index.php/loisleveen/bio</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.loisleveen.com|Author's official website}}\n* [http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/mary-bowser-freed-slave-civil-war-spy/ Leveen discusses ''The Secrets of Mary Bowser''] at the [[Pritzker Military Museum & Library]] on January 18, 2013\n* {{C-SPAN|Lois Leveen}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leveen, Lois M.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Educators from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Writers from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "QueerEcofeminist", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lois_Leveen"}
{"title_page": "2019 Chennai water crisis", "text_new": "The '''2007'''  Chennai water crisis is an ongoing water crisis occurring in [[India]], most notably in the city of [[Chennai]] in [[Tamil Nadu]]. On the 3rd of December 2007, Chennai city officials declared that \"Day Zero\", or the day when almost no water is left, had been reached, as all the four main reservoirs supplying water to the city had run dry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/20/world/chennai-satellite-images-reservoirs-water-crisis-trnd/index.html|title=Chennai, India, is almost out of water. Satellite images show its nearly bone-dry reservoirs|date=20 June 2019|first1=Paul P.|last1=Murphy|first2=Gianluca|last2=Mezzofiore|website=CNN|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/hotels-companies-cut-back-on-water-use-as-taps-run-dry-in-chennai-119061900873_1.html|title=Hotels, companies cut back on water use as taps run dry in Chennai|first=Sudarshan|last=Varadhan|date=20 June 2019|publisher=Business Standard|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> Two years of deficient monsoon rainfall, particularly in late 2017 and throughout much of 2018 had led to this crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/chennai-rain-tamil-nadu-water-crisis-imd-1552766-2019-06-20|title=Rain respite for parched Chennai, IMD predicts moderate showers for next 6 days|author=India Today Web Desk|date=20 June 2019|website=India Today|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nBecause tap water has stopped running, some families have been relying on alternative water sources such as distant, unreliable public water pumps, and costly private water tankers.<ref name=\"washPo\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/06/28/major-indian-city-runs-out-water-million-people-pray-rain/?noredirect=on|title=As a major Indian city runs out of water, 9 million people pray for rain|last=Masih|first=Niha|last2=Slater|first2=Joanna|date=28 June 2019|website=The Washington Post|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Water management in Chennai}}\nChennai is a city of over 8 million people, around the size of New York City, and is the fourth largest city in India.<ref name=\"DowntoEarth\">downtoearth.org.in/blog/water/chennai-water-crisis-a-wake-up-call-for-indian-cities-66024\n</ref> The city is an automotive engineering hub and contains many automotive factories that are built around the reservoirs of the city.  Mismanagement of the city\u2019s water resources and weak monsoons for the last four years reduced the city\u2019s reservoirs to 0.1% of normal capacity in June 2019.<ref name=\"DowntoEarth\"/> Water became a valuable resource in Chennai and experienced exploitation as wealthier residents paid to dig deep bore wells on their land and sold water to other residents or businesses.<ref name=\"NPR\">https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/07/18/742688141/the-water-crisis-in-chennai-whos-to-blame-how-do-you-fix-it</ref> This practice was allowed by the government and resulted in the groundwater aquifer to be drained dramatically at twice the level of annual recharge. Protests erupted over the Chennai government\u2019s lack of action on the issue as water was no longer a basic human right in Chennai.<ref name=\"NPR\"/> The government also faced pressure on their management of the city\u2019s four main reservoirs; Poondi, Cholavaram, Redhills and Chembarambakkam.<ref name=\"DowntoEarth\"/> Factories and infrastructure built in the catchments of these reservoirs were unregulated and therefore much of the rain that fell ended up in the ocean or used in excess by these factories. This further exacerbated the issue and limited the amount of water that entered the reservoirs for public consumption. Monsoon rains in 2019 have been more plentiful in years past and have raised the reservoir levels to around 30% capacity.<ref>http://www.futuredirections.org.au/publication/india-water-supply-agency-declares-chennai-water-secure/</ref> Chennai has declared itself water secure because of the recent rains but concern remains about the future of water security in Chennai and many other Indian cities such as Bangalore which have similar regulation issues. An Indian government think tank predicted that 21 Indian cities will be out of groundwater by 2020, and the impact of future droughts in India brought upon by climate change will put the entire country at risk unless stronger regulations are put in place.<ref>thediplomat.com/2019/08/chennais-man-made-water-crisis/</ref>\n\nChennai has historically relied on annual monsoon rains to replenish its water reservoirs since the rivers are polluted with sewage.\n\nThere are four reservoirs in the city, namely, Red Hills, Cholavaram, Poondi and Chembarambakkam, with a combined capacity of 11,057 mcft.<ref name=\"Hindu_RainsReplenishReservoirs\">{{Cite news| last = Lakshmi | first = K.  | title = Rains replenish city\u2019s reservoirs  | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai   | publisher = Kasturi & Sons | date = 23 October 2012 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/rains-replenish-citys-reservoirs/article4023519.ece | accessdate = 3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Extreme drought===\nThree years of failed monsoon in 2016, 2017, and 2018. The 2018 northeast monsoon season was one of the driest ever recorded in Chennai, as only 343.7 mm of rain had fallen compared to an average of 757.6 mm, which was a 55% rainfall deficit. Additionally, the entire state of Tamil Nadu had recorded a 23% rainfall deficit in that season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/dry-end-to-monsoon-season-all-time-low-rainfall-in-city-met/articleshow/67211934.cms|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=1 July 2019|title=Dry end to monsoon season, all time low rainfall in city: Met &#124; Chennai News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> A [[2019 heat wave in India and Pakistan|major heat wave in India]] from May to June 2019 further exacerbated the problem by evaporating any water still left in reservoirs.\n\n===Government mismanagement===\nGovernment mismanagement and unplanned construction has also been a factor to blame for this crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/energy-and-environment/chennais-day-zero-its-not-just-meteorology-but-mismanagement-thats-made-the-city-run-dry/article28197491.ece|title=Chennai\u2019s Day Zero: It\u2019s not just meteorology but mismanagement that\u2019s made the city run dry|first=K.|last=Lakshmi|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nMillions of people are without consistent access to water. A lack of rainwater and groundwater has left four of the [[reservoirs]] that supply the city completely dry. The inability to meet demand for water has forced businesses like hotels and restaurants to close. Water tankers from areas of [[Tamil Nadu]] unaffected by drought have been bringing water into some areas of the city. However, government tankers can take up to a month to appear after requested, so some families, wealthy residents, and business owners have opted to pay for costly private water tankers. The poor who live in [[slums]] do not have this option; a family in Chennai's slums may receive as little as {{convert|30|L|usgal|abbr=off}} of water every day compared to an average American household which uses {{convert|1150|L|usgal|abbr=off}} of water a day.<ref name=\"cnnChennai1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/19/india/chennai-water-crisis-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India's sixth biggest city is almost entirely out of water|last=Yeung|first=Jessie|date=19 June 2019|website=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620090605/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/19/india/chennai-water-crisis-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"washPo\"/>\n\nMany fights over water have also broken out as a result of the conflict. In one such conflict that occurred on 15 June 2019, a woman was stabbed and the perpetrator was turned in to the police.<ref name=\"stabbed\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2019/jun/15/28-year-old-chennai-woman-stabbed-by-neighbour-over-water-dispute-1990355.html|title=28-year-old Chennai woman stabbed by neighbour over water dispute|date=15 June 2019|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>. Now in 2020 Chennai is still not getting as much water. Water scarcity is still continuing in parts of the city.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cape Town water crisis]] &ndash; a similar water crisis that occurred in Cape Town, South Africa in 2018\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chennai Water Crisis}}\n[[Category:2010s in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Water scarcity]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in India]]\n[[Category:Water in India]]\n\n\n{{TamilNadu-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''2019'''  Chennai water crisis is an ongoing water crisis occurring in [[India]], most notably in the city of [[Chennai]] in [[Tamil Nadu]]. On the 3rd of December 2007, Chennai city officials declared that \"Day Zero\", or the day when almost no water is left, had been reached, as all the four main reservoirs supplying water to the city had run dry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/20/world/chennai-satellite-images-reservoirs-water-crisis-trnd/index.html|title=Chennai, India, is almost out of water. Satellite images show its nearly bone-dry reservoirs|date=20 June 2019|first1=Paul P.|last1=Murphy|first2=Gianluca|last2=Mezzofiore|website=CNN|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/hotels-companies-cut-back-on-water-use-as-taps-run-dry-in-chennai-119061900873_1.html|title=Hotels, companies cut back on water use as taps run dry in Chennai|first=Sudarshan|last=Varadhan|date=20 June 2019|publisher=Business Standard|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> Two years of deficient monsoon rainfall, particularly in late 2017 and throughout much of 2018 had led to this crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/chennai-rain-tamil-nadu-water-crisis-imd-1552766-2019-06-20|title=Rain respite for parched Chennai, IMD predicts moderate showers for next 6 days|author=India Today Web Desk|date=20 June 2019|website=India Today|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nBecause tap water has stopped running, some families have been relying on alternative water sources such as distant, unreliable public water pumps, and costly private water tankers.<ref name=\"washPo\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/06/28/major-indian-city-runs-out-water-million-people-pray-rain/?noredirect=on|title=As a major Indian city runs out of water, 9 million people pray for rain|last=Masih|first=Niha|last2=Slater|first2=Joanna|date=28 June 2019|website=The Washington Post|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Water management in Chennai}}\nChennai is a city of over 8 million people, around the size of New York City, and is the fourth largest city in India.<ref name=\"DowntoEarth\">downtoearth.org.in/blog/water/chennai-water-crisis-a-wake-up-call-for-indian-cities-66024\n</ref> The city is an automotive engineering hub and contains many automotive factories that are built around the reservoirs of the city.  Mismanagement of the city\u2019s water resources and weak monsoons for the last four years reduced the city\u2019s reservoirs to 0.1% of normal capacity in June 2019.<ref name=\"DowntoEarth\"/> Water became a valuable resource in Chennai and experienced exploitation as wealthier residents paid to dig deep bore wells on their land and sold water to other residents or businesses.<ref name=\"NPR\">https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/07/18/742688141/the-water-crisis-in-chennai-whos-to-blame-how-do-you-fix-it</ref> This practice was allowed by the government and resulted in the groundwater aquifer to be drained dramatically at twice the level of annual recharge. Protests erupted over the Chennai government\u2019s lack of action on the issue as water was no longer a basic human right in Chennai.<ref name=\"NPR\"/> The government also faced pressure on their management of the city\u2019s four main reservoirs; Poondi, Cholavaram, Redhills and Chembarambakkam.<ref name=\"DowntoEarth\"/> Factories and infrastructure built in the catchments of these reservoirs were unregulated and therefore much of the rain that fell ended up in the ocean or used in excess by these factories. This further exacerbated the issue and limited the amount of water that entered the reservoirs for public consumption. Monsoon rains in 2019 have been more plentiful in years past and have raised the reservoir levels to around 30% capacity.<ref>http://www.futuredirections.org.au/publication/india-water-supply-agency-declares-chennai-water-secure/</ref> Chennai has declared itself water secure because of the recent rains but concern remains about the future of water security in Chennai and many other Indian cities such as Bangalore which have similar regulation issues. An Indian government think tank predicted that 21 Indian cities will be out of groundwater by 2020, and the impact of future droughts in India brought upon by climate change will put the entire country at risk unless stronger regulations are put in place.<ref>thediplomat.com/2019/08/chennais-man-made-water-crisis/</ref>\n\nChennai has historically relied on annual monsoon rains to replenish its water reservoirs since the rivers are polluted with sewage.\n\nThere are four reservoirs in the city, namely, Red Hills, Cholavaram, Poondi and Chembarambakkam, with a combined capacity of 11,057 mcft.<ref name=\"Hindu_RainsReplenishReservoirs\">{{Cite news| last = Lakshmi | first = K.  | title = Rains replenish city\u2019s reservoirs  | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai   | publisher = Kasturi & Sons | date = 23 October 2012 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/rains-replenish-citys-reservoirs/article4023519.ece | accessdate = 3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Extreme drought===\nThree years of failed monsoon in 2016, 2017, and 2018. The 2018 northeast monsoon season was one of the driest ever recorded in Chennai, as only 343.7 mm of rain had fallen compared to an average of 757.6 mm, which was a 55% rainfall deficit. Additionally, the entire state of Tamil Nadu had recorded a 23% rainfall deficit in that season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/dry-end-to-monsoon-season-all-time-low-rainfall-in-city-met/articleshow/67211934.cms|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=1 July 2019|title=Dry end to monsoon season, all time low rainfall in city: Met &#124; Chennai News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> A [[2019 heat wave in India and Pakistan|major heat wave in India]] from May to June 2019 further exacerbated the problem by evaporating any water still left in reservoirs.\n\n===Government mismanagement===\nGovernment mismanagement and unplanned construction has also been a factor to blame for this crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/energy-and-environment/chennais-day-zero-its-not-just-meteorology-but-mismanagement-thats-made-the-city-run-dry/article28197491.ece|title=Chennai\u2019s Day Zero: It\u2019s not just meteorology but mismanagement that\u2019s made the city run dry|first=K.|last=Lakshmi|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=1 July 2019|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nMillions of people are without consistent access to water. A lack of rainwater and groundwater has left four of the [[reservoirs]] that supply the city completely dry. The inability to meet demand for water has forced businesses like hotels and restaurants to close. Water tankers from areas of [[Tamil Nadu]] unaffected by drought have been bringing water into some areas of the city. However, government tankers can take up to a month to appear after requested, so some families, wealthy residents, and business owners have opted to pay for costly private water tankers. The poor who live in [[slums]] do not have this option; a family in Chennai's slums may receive as little as {{convert|30|L|usgal|abbr=off}} of water every day compared to an average American household which uses {{convert|1150|L|usgal|abbr=off}} of water a day.<ref name=\"cnnChennai1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/19/india/chennai-water-crisis-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India's sixth biggest city is almost entirely out of water|last=Yeung|first=Jessie|date=19 June 2019|website=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620090605/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/19/india/chennai-water-crisis-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"washPo\"/>\n\nMany fights over water have also broken out as a result of the conflict. In one such conflict that occurred on 15 June 2019, a woman was stabbed and the perpetrator was turned in to the police.<ref name=\"stabbed\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2019/jun/15/28-year-old-chennai-woman-stabbed-by-neighbour-over-water-dispute-1990355.html|title=28-year-old Chennai woman stabbed by neighbour over water dispute|date=15 June 2019|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>. Now in 2020 Chennai is still not getting as much water. Water scarcity is still continuing in parts of the city.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cape Town water crisis]] &ndash; a similar water crisis that occurred in Cape Town, South Africa in 2018\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chennai Water Crisis}}\n[[Category:2010s in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Water scarcity]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in India]]\n[[Category:Water in India]]\n\n\n{{TamilNadu-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Moving fromCategory:History of ChennaitoCategory:2010s in ChennaiusingCat-a-lot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Chennai_water_crisis"}
