adium]], [[Kaunas]] || {{fb|LTU}} || 1\u20130 || 2\u20131 || [[2008 UEFA European Football Championship|UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying]] || <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres2010.html |title=Scotland International Matches 2006-2010 |website= |publisher=RSSSF |first=Gabriele |last=Tossani |date=11 April 2019 |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n; Dundee United:\n* Scottish Cup winner: [[1994 Scottish Cup Final|1994]]\n\n; West Ham United:\n* Championship play-off winner: [[2005 Football League Championship play-off Final|2005]]\n* FA Cup runner-up: [[2006 FA Cup Final|2006]]\n\n; Rangers:\n* Scottish Premier League winner: [[Scottish Premier League 2008-09|2008-09]]\n* Scottish Cup winner: [[2008 Scottish Cup Final|2008]], [[2009 Scottish Cup Final|2009]]\n* Scottish League Cup winner: [[2008 Scottish League Cup Final|2008]]\n* UEFA Cup runner-up: [[UEFA Cup 2007-08|2008]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Scotland national football team roll of honour]] : 2003\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[http://www.eu-football.info/_player.php?id=4171 International career details]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Awards\n|bg = gold\n|fg = navy\n|list1 =\n{{Charlton Athletic F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Dundee United F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Scotland Squad 1998 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dailly, Christian}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Dundee]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Christian Dailly\n| image          = ChristianDailly.jpg\n| image_size     = 150\n| caption        = Dailly warms-up for West Ham United at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]]\n| fullname       = Christian Eduard Dailly<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11 105\">{{Cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311\n | year = 2010\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-601-0\n | page = 105 }}</ref>\n| height         = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=y|1973|10|23}}\n| birth_place    = [[Dundee]], Scotland\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]] / [[Utility player]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1990\u20131996 | caps1 = 143 | goals1 = 18 | clubs1 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n| years2 = 1996\u20131998 | caps2 = 67  | goals2 = 4  | clubs2 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]\n| years3 = 1998\u20132001 | caps3 = 70  | goals3 = 4  | clubs3 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| years4 = 2001\u20132007 | caps4 = 158 | goals4 = 3  | clubs4 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]\n| years5 = 2007      | caps5 = 11  | goals5 = 0  | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] (loan) \n| years6 = 2008\u20132009 | caps6 = 21  | goals6 = 2  | clubs6 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| years7 = 2009\u20132011 | caps7 = 78  | goals7 = 1  | clubs7 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]\n| years8 = 2011      | caps8 = 1   | goals8 = 0  | clubs8 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| years9 = 2012      | caps9 = 3   | goals9 = 0  | clubs9 = [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]\n| totalcaps      = 552\n| totalgoals     = 32\n<!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES & GOALS ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 1990\u20131996 \n| nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]<ref name = \"u21\">http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu21/player.php?playerid=171</ref>\n| nationalyears2 = 1997\u20132008 \n| nationalteam2  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 35\n| nationalgoals1 = 5\n| nationalcaps2  = 67\n| nationalgoals2 = 6\n}}\n'''Christian Eduard Dailly''' (born 23 October 1973) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|footballer]]. A versatile player, he was often seen in central defence, although he played in most outfield positions during his career.\n\nHe started his professional career as a teenager, playing as a [[forward (association football)|striker]] for [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]. He helped them win the [[1993\u201394 Scottish Cup]]. Towards the end of his time with United, Dailly began playing as a [[Defender (association football)|central defender]]. He moved to English [[Premier League]] club [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in 1996. After two seasons with Derby, Dailly moved to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] for a transfer fee of \u00a35,350,000. During his time with Blackburn, the club were relegated in [[1998\u201399 in English football|1999]] and Dailly lost his place in the team.\n\nHe moved to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2001 for \u00a31,700,000. During his time with West Ham, the club were relegated in [[2002\u201303 in English football|2003]] but won promotion in [[2004\u201305 in English football|2005]]. Dailly appeared as a substitute in the [[2006 FA Cup Final]], which West Ham lost on [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]] to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. After a loan spell with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], Dailly moved to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in January 2008. He helped the team reach the [[2008 UEFA Cup Final]]. His final appearance for Rangers was as a substitute in the [[2009 Scottish Cup Final]], which Rangers won 1\u20130 against [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]. After a two-year spell with [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] and short stints with [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] and [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]], Dailly retired in 2012.\n\nDailly made 67 full international appearances for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] between 1997 and 2008. He was part of the Scotland squad at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. Dailly is also the record cap-holder for the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21]] team, having made 35 appearances between 1990 and 1996.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Dundee United===\nDailly was born in [[Dundee]] and first signed professional terms with [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 2 August 1990, aged sixteen years old. He became the youngest-ever player to appear for Dundee United when he made his first-team debut on 21 August 1990, though this record has since been broken by [[Greg Cameron]]. Playing as a striker and scoring in each of his first three games, Dailly quickly shot to prominence, making his [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland Under 21 side]] debut just a month later. He won the [[Scottish Youth Cup]] with the club in 1990\u201391.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/famous-faces-youth-cup-final/ | title=Famous Faces \u2013 Youth Cup Final | publisher=[[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] | date=19 May 2015 | accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref> In his debut season, Dailly managed five goals in eighteen appearances. His debut season would become his most prolific, and the 1991\u201392 season brought just eight games with no goals. In the 1992\u201393 season, Dailly scored four from fourteen appearances and firmly established himself as a regular in the 1993\u201394 season with 38 league appearances, and not only another four goals, but also the [[Scottish Cup]], when his shot rebounded off the post for [[Craig Brewster]] to score the only goal against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].\n\nThe [[1994\u201395 Dundee United F.C. season|1994\u201395]] season ended in disappointment with relegation, with yet another four goals from 33 games. In [[1995\u201396 Dundee United F.C. season|1995\u201396]], Dailly was firmly established as a central defender and started the season as United's club captain, although he was subsequently replaced by [[David Bowman (footballer born 1964)|Dave Bowman]]. He scored just once in 30 appearances. It was an important goal though, as it ensured United drew the away leg of the short-lived league-playoff against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], and subsequently won the home leg to gain promotion at the first opportunity. This proved to be Dailly's final game for Dundee United, as he joined Derby County in August 1996 for \u00a3500,000, with a further \u00a3500,000 payable dependent on his international career, which was later paid.\n\n===Derby County===\nDailly joined Derby County at the start of the [[1996\u201397 Derby County F.C. season|1996\u201397]] season, following Derby's promotion to the [[Premier League|FA Premier League]]. In his debut English season, Dailly missed just two games, with his three goals helping Derby to 12th place and six points clear of relegation. In the [[1997\u201398 Derby County F.C. season|1997\u201398]] season, Dailly made 30 appearances and scored once; Derby fared even better, with the club finishing ninth and just two points from European football. In [[1998\u201399 Derby County F.C. season|1998\u201399]], Dailly played just once, coincidentally against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], the club to which he was then transferred.\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nDailly joined Rovers in August 1998 for \u00a35.35m but a [[1998\u201399 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|tumultuous]] season followed with Dailly not finding a settled position and an injury meaning he played just seventeen times. To make matters worse, Rovers were relegated from the [[Premier League|FA Premier League]] as Dailly suffered relegation for the second time in his career. In the [[Football League First Division|First Division]], Dailly appeared 43 times in a hectic [[1999\u20132000 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|1999\u20132000]] season, which saw him score four goals. However, he fell out of favour with new boss [[Graeme Souness]] and in January 2001, after making just nine appearances that season, Dailly left for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a \u00a31.75m deal and returned to the Premier League. During his spell at Blackburn he played in a testimonial match for [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] \u2013 scoring a late consolation goal against Liverpool in the Ronnie Moran testimonial match on 13 May 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ronniemoran.com/testimonial.htm |title=Testimonial match versus Celtic, 13 May 2000 |publisher=Ronnie Moran |date= |accessdate=11 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928093657/http://www.ronniemoran.com/testimonial.htm |archive-date=28 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\nFollowing his transfer from Blackburn to the Hammers for a fee of \u00a31.7m he made twelve appearances in [[2000\u201301 West Ham United F.C. season|2000\u201301]], helping the Hammers to 15th place. He also played in their 1\u20130 victory over Manchester United at [[Old Trafford]] in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/1140138.stm\n|title=Di Canio sinks Man Utd\n|publisher=BBC Sport\n|date=28 January 2001\n|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref> The following season, Dailly played every minute of every game as West Ham finished in seventh place. [[2002\u201303 West Ham United F.C. season|2002\u201303]] proved to be a low point, as Daily suffered relegation for a third time. Playing 26 times, West Ham were relegated with the highest number of points since the 1995\u201396 change to 20 teams, a total of 42.\n\nDailly was to go on and score twice from 43 games as West Ham finished in the Division One play-off positions in [[2003\u201304 West Ham United F.C. season|2003\u201304]]. He scored the winner against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in the play-off semi-final to send them to the final<ref name=\"posemi\">{{cite web |accessdate=2012-01-11|publisher=www.sportinglife.com| url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/cc_championship/westham/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/04/05/18/SOCCER_West_Ham.html&TEAMHD=westham&DIV=nat1&TEAM=WEST--HAM&RH=West--Ham&PREV_SEASON=2002 | title=West Ham 2 Ipswich 0 (Agg: 2\u20131)}}</ref> but they failed to win promotion. Injury prevented Dailly from the majority of West Ham's promotion-winning [[2004\u201305 West Ham United F.C. season|2004\u201305]] season, although he returned to make brief appearances in one [[Football League Championship playoffs|play-off]] semi-final leg and the final. He signed a new deal with West Ham in June 2005.<ref name=\"Dailly signs new Hammers contract\">{{cite news| title = Dailly signs new Hammers contract | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/4083524.stm | publisher = BBC Sport website | date = 11 June 2005 | accessdate = 8 July 2007}}</ref> Dailly appeared as a substitute for West Ham in their [[2006 FA Cup Final]] defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], coming on in the 77th minute. Despite being 2\u20130 ahead after 28 minutes, West Ham eventually lost on penalties. He was the longest serving West Ham player at the time of his departure and something of a cult hero to the fans.<ref>{{cite news|author=Russell Brand |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/mar/03/sport.comment3 |title=Russell Brand: It is time to face facts \u2013 we are all doomed &#124; Football |publisher=The Guardian |date= 3 March 2007|accessdate=2011-09-02 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Southampton===\nOn 20 September 2007, he joined [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on loan, initially for a month. The loan was extended for a further month as Saints continued to suffer with injuries to several defensive players.<ref>{{cite news| title = Christian aid for Saints | url = http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/saints/news/display.var.1704557.0.christian_aid_for_saints.php | publisher = dailyecho | date = 20 September 2007 | accessdate = 20 September 2007}}</ref> He made his debut against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] in a 3\u20132 home league defeat on 22 September 2007. After eleven appearances for Saints he returned to West Ham.\n\n===Rangers===\nOn 30 January 2008, Dailly signed for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on a short term contract until the end of the season. The club took over what remained of his contract from [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Gers sign Dailly| url = http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Headlines/0,,5~1229044,00.html| publisher = Rangers official website| date = 30 January 2008}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He made his Rangers debut three weeks later in a [[UEFA Cup]] match against [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]; the game ended in a 1\u20131 and saw the club progress to the fourth round.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7254789.stm Panathinaikos 1\u20131 Rangers] BBC Sport website, 21 February 2008</ref> He scored his first goal 9 days later, netting the equaliser in a 3\u20131 triumph over [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref name=\"Dailly first Gers goal\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/7270219.stm|title=Rangers 3\u20131 Aberdeen|publisher=BBC Sport website|date=1 March 2008|first=David|last=Sharp}}</ref> On 3 July 2008 he and [[David Weir (Scottish footballer)|David Weir]] signed new one-year contract extensions with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/7487125.stm|title=Veteran duo seal new Ibrox deals|date=3 July 2008|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Dailly continued to play as part of the Rangers squad as they progressed to the 2008 UEFA Cup Final in Manchester.\n\nThe arrival of [[Madjid Bougherra]] then saw Dailly lose his place in the team until an injury to Bougherra saw him included in Rangers' [[2009 Scottish League Cup Final]] squad. He played his final game for the club in the [[2009 Scottish Cup Final]] as an 87th-minute substitute helping Rangers retain the Scottish Cup in a 1\u20130 victory over Falkirk. He was released two days later on 1 June 2009. Dailly made 36 appearances in total and scored twice for Rangers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8077300.stm|title=Weir poised for new Rangers deal |date=1 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\nOn 31 July 2009 Dailly signed for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on a [[Bosman ruling|Bosman]] free transfer and took squad number 35, his then age.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/8174479.stm |title=Addicks bring in veteran Dailly |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 July 2009 |accessdate=2011-09-02}}</ref> His debut for Charlton came on 8 August 2009 in a 3\u20132 home win against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]], a game which saw Dailly score his only Charlton goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/8186068.stm |title=Charlton 3\u20132 Wycombe |publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 August 2009 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> At the end of the [[2009\u201310 Charlton Athletic F.C. season|2009\u201310]] season he was named as Charlton Athletic's player of the year. \"I feel very proud\", Dailly told the official website.<ref>[http://www.charlton-athletic.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=36053&newstype=p]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth===\nDailly joined Portsmouth on a one-month deal in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/sport/pompey/pompey-past/great-matches/pompey_sign_dailly_1_2940898 |title=Pompey sign Dailly \u2013 Great Matches \u2013 The News |publisher=Portsmouth.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-09-02}}</ref> He made his debut on 6 August 2011, in the 2\u20132 away draw against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], after coming off the bench to replace [[Hayden Mullins]].<ref>[https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2011/08/06/england/championship/middlesbrough-football-club/portsmouth-football-club/1119636/ Middlesbrough vs. Portsmouth 2\u20132]</ref> On 1 September 2011 he was released having made just two appearances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2032789/Christian-Dailly-released-Portsmouth.html |title=Christian Dailly released by Portsmouth |newspaper=Daily Mail |date= 1 September 2011|accessdate=2011-09-02 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Southend United===\nOn 16 March 2012 Dailly signed for [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] on non-contract terms, following several months training with the club to recuperate from a knee injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10444~2662330,00.html |title=One In, Two Out |publisher=Southend United F.C. |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=2012-03-16 |location=Southend |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318220437/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10444~2662330%2C00.html |archivedate=18 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dailly made his debut for Southend on 17 March 2012, playing 90 minutes in the 3\u20132 win at [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hereford 2\u20133 Southend|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17323903|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref> In Dailly's third appearance for the club, against [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] on 24 March 2012, he broke his toe ruling him out for the remainder of the season.<ref name=Toe>{{cite web|title=Christian Dailly injury blow for Southend United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17537119|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> Dailly retired from professional football in July 2012, after 22 years in the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Football news in brief: Sasa Papac on verge of move to La Liga's Osasuna|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/top-football-stories/football-news-in-brief-sasa-papac-on-verge-of-move-to-la-liga-s-osasuna-1-2400559|accessdate=9 July 2012|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 11 September 1990, Dailly became the youngest player to appear for his country at [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 level]] when he featured at the age of 16 against [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania]] at [[Easter Road]]. By the time Dailly was too old to continue playing at this level he had received 35 caps,<ref name = \"u21\"/> a Scottish record for appearances at under-21 level.<ref name=\"SFA\">{{SFA Profile|id=8755}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1993, he was included in [[Andy Roxburgh]]'s Scotland squad for the first time for a [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification]] match in [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]]. He earned his first cap four years later when he made his full international debut in May 1997, aged 23, in a 1\u20130 defeat against [[Wales national football team|Wales]]. His first goal came in just his second match, and just four days after his international debut, when his early goal helped Scotland to a 3\u20132 away victory over [[Malta national football team|Malta]] in a friendly match.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nDailly had a long Scotland career, winning 67 caps and scoring 6 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138|title=International Roll of Honour|publisher=Scottish Football Association|accessdate=17 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011104402/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138|archivedate=11 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He captained Scotland a total of 12 times and was selected for the Scotland squad at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. Dailly won his last cap as a substitute on Friday 30 May 2008, in a 3\u20131 friendly defeat against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].\n\nDailly was famously caught unaware after Germany's 2\u20131 defeat of Scotland on 10 September 2003. He returned to the dressing room after the match shouting, \"Cheats! Fucking cheats! Fucking diving cheats!\" The outburst was being broadcast live on [[BBC Scotland]] as then Scotland manager [[Berti Vogts]] was being interviewed by [[Chick Young]]. The player would have remained anonymous had it not been for Vogts shouting \"Christian!\" mid-interview to stop the tirade.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/sport.cfm?id=1007502003 |title= Dailly's outburst is hardly Christian |work= The Scotsman |date= 12 September 2003 |accessdate= 11 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071211164240/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/sport.cfm?id=1007502003 |archivedate=11 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis sister, Stefani Dailly, is a broadcast journalist who has worked for ''[[STV News]]''.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/tv-signing-another-score-for-sporting-families-1-601443 TV signing another score for sporting families], The Scotsman, 29 March 2003</ref>\n\nHis son, Harvey, signed a development contract with Dundee United in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34111162 |title=Dundee United: Harvey Dailly follows father Christian to Tannadice |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=1 September 2015 |accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> He made his first team debut in August 2017,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roache|first1=Ian|title=Like father, like son: Harvey and Christian Dailly join select Dundee United club|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/dundee-united/491482/like-father-like-son-harvey-christian-dailly-join-select-dundee-united-club/|accessdate=16 August 2017|work=The Courier|date=16 August 2017|location=Dundee}}</ref> but was released in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Christian Dailly's son Harvey one of two players to leave Dundee United|url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/christian-daillys-son-harvey-one-two-players-leave-dundee-united/|accessdate=16 January 2018|work=Evening Telegraph|date=16 January 2018|location=Dundee}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Club\n! rowspan=2 | Season\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Other<ref>Includes [[UEFA|Europe]], [[Football League play-offs]]</ref>\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n! Apps\n! Goals\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| rowspan=\"7\" style=\"vertical-align:top;\"|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|[[1990\u201391 Dundee United F.C. season|1990\u201391]]\n|18||5||2||0||4||2||2||0||26||7\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1991\u201392 Dundee United F.C. season|1991\u201392]]\n|8||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||8||0\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1992\u201393 Dundee United F.C. season|1992\u201393]]\n|14||4||1||0||0||0||0||0||15||4\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1993\u201394 Dundee United F.C. season|1993\u201394]]\n|38||3||6||0||4||0||2||0||50||3\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1994\u201395 Dundee United F.C. season|1994\u201395]]\n|33||4||4||0||1||0||2||0||40||4\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1995\u201396 Dundee 